Name: Acid Soluble
Description: That portion of the analyte which becomes dissolved within the sample following treatment with an appropriate acid.

Name: Bioavailable
Description: The extent to which a substance is / becomes available or absorbed by a specific tissue or organ.

Name: Comb Available
Description: The Concentration of a analyte or other analyte derivatives in a water which is combined with other derivatives yet is still available to oxidize organic matter.

Name: Dissolved
Description: That portion of the analyte found in the liquid medium.  Cannot be removed by filtration.

Name: Extractable
Description: An analyte that can be removed from a mixture using a specific method or technique

Name: Filterable
Description: That portion of the analyte which is in or absorbed to material which passes through the filter during sample filtration.

Name: Filtered, field
Description: Performed in field. +/ Pertains to constituents in a water sample passed through a filter membrane of specified pore diameter, 0.45 µm or less for inorganic analytes and 0.7 µm for organic analytes.

Name: Filtered, lab
Description: Performed in lab. +/ Pertains to constituents in a water sample passed through a filter membrane of specified pore diameter, 0.45 µm or less for inorganic analytes and 0.7 µm for organic analytes.

Name: Fixed
Description: That portion of the analyte found in the liquid layer above a precipitate produced from the sample.

Name: Free Available
Description: The concentration of residual substance present as dissolved gas, and not combined with any substance or in other less readily available form.

Name: Inorganic
Description: Inorganic content of sample

Name: Non-Filterable (Particle)
Description: That portion of the analyte which is extracted from the liquid medium by filtration.

Name: Non-settleable
Description: That portion of the analyte which is in or absorbed to particles remaining in suspension in the sample container after a settling process.

Name: Non-volatile
Description: That portion of the analyte which is in a liquid or solid state under normal temperature and pressure.

Name: None
Description: None or Not Applicable

Name: Organic
Description: Organic content of a sample

Name: Pot. Dissolved
Description: Potentially Dissolved is the portion of a constituent measured from the filtrate of a water and suspended sediment sample that was treated with nitric acid prior to sample filtration.

Name: Semivolatile
Description: The portion of the analyte which semi-easily enter the air as gases from some solids or liquids.

Name: Settleable
Description: That portion of the analyte which is found in or absorbed to that part of the sample which has settled (fallen out of suspension) to the bottom of the sample container.

Name: Strong Acid Diss
Description: Strong Acid Dissociable, analyte that is released from analyte containing compounds under highly acidic conditions.

Name: Supernate
Description: That portion of the analyte found in the liquid layer above a precipitate produced from the sample.

Name: Suspended
Description: That portion of the analyte which is suspended in the sampled medium, either as, or adsorbed to, particles which are more or less uniformly dispersed within the medium.

Name: Total
Description: The total of all fractions of the analyte.

Name: Total Recoverable
Description: The analyte concentration available for analysis in an unfiltered sample following solubilization.

Name: Total Residual
Description: The amount of available analyte remaining after a given contact time. The sum of the combined available residual analyte and the free available residual analyte.

Name: Total Soluble
Description: The total of all fractions of the analyte / The sum of all of the different forms of the analyte present which becomes dissolved within the sample.

Name: Unfiltered
Description: Pertains to the constituents in a representative water-suspended-solids sample. (whole)

Name: Vapor
Description: That portion of the analyte which exists in a gaseous state and that under ordinary conditions is liquid or solid.

Name: Volatile
Description: That portion of the analyte which evaporates readily at normal temperature and pressure.

Name: Weak Acid Diss
Description: Weak Acid Dissociable, analyte that is readily released from analyte containing compounds when the pH is lowered.
